aa(lp23
VMy best friend Steve,
p24
aVsensing that something was terribly wrong,
p25
aVflew out to New Haven to be with me.
p26
aVNow I'm going to quote from some of my writings:
p27
aV"I opened the door to my studio apartment.
p28
aVSteve would later tell me that,
p29
aVfor all the times he had seen me psychotic, nothing
p30
aVcould have prepared him for what he saw that day.
p31
aVFor a week or more, I had barely eaten.
p32
aVI was gaunt. I walked
p33
aVas though my legs were wooden.
p34
aVMy face looked and felt like a mask.
p35
aVI had closed all the curtains in the apartment, so
p36
aVin the middle of the day
p37
aVthe apartment was in near total darkness.
p38
aVThe air was fetid, the room a shambles.
p39
aVSteve, both a lawyer and a psychologist, has treated
p40
aVmany patients with severe mental illness, and to this day
p41
aVhe'll say I was as bad as any he had ever seen.
p42
aV'Hi,' I said, and then I returned to the couch,
p43
aVwhere I sat in silence for several moments.
p44
aV'Thank you for coming, Steve.
p45
aVCrumbling world, word, voice.
p46
aVTell the clocks to stop.
p47
aVTime is. Time has come.'
p48
aV'White is leaving,' Steve said somberly.
p49
aV'I'm being pushed into a grave. The situation is grave,' I moan.
p50
aV'Gravity is pulling me down.
p51
aVI'm scared. Tell them to get away.'"
